In a little-noticed statement on Monday, @realdonaldtrump predicted that the Wuhan coronavirus currently ravaging parts of China would “miraculously” go away once the weather “warms up.” See USA Today, “Trump says Coronavirus will be gone by April when the weather gets warmer.”

As scientists across the world struggle to understand the novel coronavirus, conspiracy theorists are already disseminating misinformation. We don’t need the president fanning the flames of ignorance by making ill-informed statements that have no basis. Listen to health

authorities, not Trump. Trump’s actions are irresponsible. The press and political leaders should condemn Trump in words of one syllable. Trump is endangering the health of the American people—and not just with his ignorant comment about the Wuhan coronavirus. On Monday,

Trump released his proposed budget for 2020-2021. Per the Washington Post, Trump’s budget would slash the Environmental Protection Agency budget by 26.5 percent over the next year and cut the Department of Health and Human Services budget by 9 percent. HHS includes the National
Institutes of Health and the Centers for Disease Control, which would see a budget cut even as it is under intense scrutiny over its response to the coronavirus.
While administration officials claim they aren’t cutting money from the “disease prevention” function of NIH, that remains to be seen. The timing for an attack on NIH couldn’t have been worse.
